Function specializations for big-but-trivial callables

Summary:
When the callable is big but trivially-copyable, we can share destroy operations between all instances. There is not even any need to split them by size, as is done for small trivially-copyable callables, since there is extra space in the buffer to store the size and even the alignment.

As hypothesis, many big callables stored in a `Function` are also trivially-copyable, storing mostly references but also and pointers and arithmetic types.

fbshipit-source-id: 5ba915b0f1b6c8f501d72ab2c27ff610f7b680c6

cut use of std::move over lambdas in futures

Summary:
Each separate use of `std::move`, at least specifically over a lambda, tends to be a separate function template instantiation.

Contrast this with the use of `std::move` over the value-type of a `Future`; typically, there will be many uses of `Future` with the same value-type, and the use of `std::move` over the same value-type will appear many times, so that the function template instantiation is done once for each such value-type and its cost amortizes over all uses.

Reviewed By: Gownta
